    {
        "content": "<p>While you can use <code>\\prod j \\in Finset.Icc 1 k, f j</code>, the API works much better if you start indexes with <code>0</code>.</p>",
        "id": 572576468,
        "sender_full_name": "Yury G. Kudryashov",
        "timestamp": 1770509275
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I would reconsider reindexing from <code>0</code>.</p>",
        "id": 572576491,
        "sender_full_name": "Yury G. Kudryashov",
        "timestamp": 1770509294
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Also, do you want a predicate or a definition? What kind of statements do you want to formulate? Are you going to submit it to Mathlib? Some other repo? An AI company? Something else?</p>",
        "id": 572576625,
        "sender_full_name": "Yury G. Kudryashov",
        "timestamp": 1770509401
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The last question affects coding style decisions a lot.</p>",
        "id": 572576648,
        "sender_full_name": "Yury G. Kudryashov",
        "timestamp": 1770509432
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Right now the answer is \"something else\".  If the results are useful for Mathlib or some other organization, then I am likely to turn the results over for refactoring by someone else.  However, I want to use this as an example to teach others, and so I want to follow the notation from the literature.  Also, some results don't hold if I use n+id for 0&lt;=i&lt;k .  So I am at present attached to the literature indexing (which has n+d, n+2d, ..., n+kd) and am hoping for a different idiom.</p>\n<p>One statement I am working towards has the shape: if  &lt;n+id&gt; is an irreducible arithmetic progression and (some other property), then &lt;g(n+id)&gt; (g mapping on &lt;n+id&gt;) is a sequence with duplicate entries.  (I am omitting the indexing right now for brevity.)</p>",
        "id": 572578050,
        "sender_full_name": "J. J. Issai (project started by GRP)",
        "timestamp": 1770511459
    }
